Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in machine reading comprehension (MRC) with unanswerable questions lies not just in detecting whether a question can be answered, but in understanding *why*—what subtle semantic or syntactic shifts render a seemingly plausible query unanswerable. Existing methods like span-based contrastive learning (Paper 1) focus on contrasting answerable and unanswerable question pairs at the surface level of answer spans, but they do not explicitly model the *latent structural schema* that underlies valid answerability. I argue that answer spans are more than mere text segments—they implicitly encode a "schema" of what constitutes a valid response: including entity types, relational roles, temporal constraints, and logical coherence with the passage. By treating these spans as latent schemas, we can build a contrastive learning framework that not only discriminates relevance (is this question answerable?) but also calibrates difficulty (how close is it semantically to being answerable?). This idea diverges from prior work by shifting from surface-level span comparison to schema-level alignment, integrating mutual information maximization (inspired by Paper 2) to ensure that the learned representations preserve meaningful correlations between questions and their feasible answer structures. Furthermore, drawing from contrastive explanations (Paper 3), we design our model to generate interpretable signals about *which features differentiate* answerable from unanswerable cases. Unlike previous approaches, our method does not assume that unanswerable questions are random negatives; instead, it constructs them as *schema-mismatched* variants—questions that superficially align with the passage but violate one or more constraints encoded in the latent schema. This enables fine-grained control over both relevance discrimination and difficulty calibration, leading to more robust and interpretable MRC systems.

